title: For Sale/Trade:  1977 American Eagle Arms Corp 45 cal black-powder Muzzle loader
postcontent:
Norman, REDACTED, $150 OBO
Hey everyone, 
I have an old Blackpowder for sale or trade. It is a American Eagle Arms Corp 45 caliber. It is almost an exact clone of a thompson center hawken rifle. It is made in Italy and is in pretty good shape for its age. I have been told by 4 different people that it was probably imported in the 70's or so from the italian company who also makes the guns for hawken or lymon. This was proofed in 1977 due to the stamping it has on it. It isstamped made in italy and has the proof marks as well. It looks to be an originally "browned" gun instead of the regular blued. If not, then the patina is really good and gives the steel that "browned" look. The only thing this may need is the brass jag on one end of the ram rod is missing. I looked and you can get a replacement for pretty cheap (literally like 5 dollars on some sites), but overall this is a really good gun that mainly just needs a really good cleaning and oiling down. This is actually a pretty decent gun and would be a great setup for someone wanting to be more traditional that all these inline muzzleloaders out there. I would keep this for myself but I already have a Lymon 50 and a Thompson 54 and really dont want to have to make a bunch of rounds for this gun as well. So I am passing it on to yall to play with!

title: For Sale/Trade:  DWM German Luger P08 ca. 1916
postcontent:
Up for trade is a German Luger P08 chambered in 9mm. It was manufactured by DWM in 1916. Most of the numbers match, however the grips, side plate, and one one other small piece (not sure what it would be called) are of a different SN. It does however have a matching magazine which is a relatively rare occurrence. The matching mag has a small piece of wood missing from the baseplate however it still holds ammunition. For this reason I have never fired any rounds out of the original magazine. The spare magazine is fine. I've put two mags down range and it would not cycle 115gr FMJ, but had no problem with 125gr lead round nose. (I've read numerous times that the P08 doesn't like anything less than 124gr) I have no papers or history on the gun. The finish appears all original, no rust, and action locks up tight.

title: For Sale/Trade:  .38 Special Under Cover Charter Arms
postcontent:
Charter Arms Under Cover.38 Special Revolver
I have owned this handgun for almost 25 years.  It has never failed to fire.  Granted, I have NOT shot thousands of rounds through it.  The pistol has had maybe at most a few boxes of shells through it over the years.  It wound up being an under the seat or bedside gun for many years but does not show a lot of wear as it was kept in a small gun case most of the time.  It fits well into a pocket. For the last several years it has been sitting lonely in my gun cabinet. 
First and foremost, this is an American made gun.  It was designed by Douglas McClenahan who had previously worked for Colt, High Standard, and Ruger before he founded Charter Arms in 1964. When Charter introduced the Undercover, at 16 ounces, this was the smallest, lightest, steel framed revolver in the world with the fewest moving parts and included a then unique hammer block safety.  The innovative design of the revolver included a one piece frame (with no side plate) which gave the gun additional strength and allows it to safely shoot high pressure loads.  Several of the Charter innovations have been copied over the years by much larger manufacturers.  Due to its continuing popularity, the undercover is still in production.  As such,  there are a wide array of new grips, lasers, holsters, etc. that will fit this revolver.  The suggested retail for new Charter Arms Undercover .38 special revolvers is between $330 to over $425 depending on the exact model.

Contact me by phone or preferably text at 770-283-seven seven five 2

title: For Sale:  LWRC -- M6.8-A2 6.8 SPC II SIX8 Zeiss Victory for BIN
postcontent:
The SIX8™ weapons are short-stroke, gas-piston operated rifles chambered in the 6.8x43mm SPC cartridge. This cartridge was developed as part of the Enhanced Rifle Cartridge Program in which U.S. Special Operations soldiers, as well as armorers and other technicians from the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit, played a major role. Its primary purpose was to address the deficiencies in terminal performance seen with the 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge, while allowing the soldier to carry the same number of rounds with minimal weight penalty. It succeeds in doing so because it uses a heavier bullet with excellent accuracy, which delivers more energy across all effective ranges.

Until now, a major drawback of using the 6.8 cartridge in an M4 style weapon has been the lack of reliable magazines. So, when we designed the SIX8™ family of weapons, we started with the magazine. Partnering with Magpul®, the leader in polymer magazine engineering, we designed the first polymer 6.8 magazine. Building upon the magazine, we designed the SIX8™ platform for maximum reliability and improved ergonomics. The upper and lower receivers are designed to accommodate the slightly larger polymer magazine and to perfect the feed geometry for the 6.8 cartridge. In addition, we have prompted Federal Ammunition to develop new lines of affordably priced, high performance 6.8 ammunition for commercial, law enforcement and military applications.

As with the IC family, the weapons in the new SIX8™ family are fully ambidextrous and equally suited to right- or left-handed operators. The SIX8™ rifles are based on the familiar Stoner M4/AR15/M16 architecture, but they have been optimized specifically for use with the 6.8 cartridge.

The new SIX8™ family combines the ultimate in ergonomic user-friendly rifles with the outstanding mid-range 6.8 cartridge.

title: For Sale:  Aimpoint Pro Patrol Rifle Red Dot Optic
postcontent:
I am selling my new Aimpoint Pro Patrol Rifle Optic. I am sure everyone has heard of the company EO Tech, which produces weapon sights commonly referred to as a "Red Dot". 

For those of you who are not familiar with Aimpoint, they are the less known company that produces optic for Military/LE. 

In my first hand experience with using many different weapon optics as a Police Officer, I prefer many Aimpoint optics to EO Tech products due to a much longer battery life and lightweight design. 

The Aimpoint Pro is a Patrol Rifle Optic with a "Red Dot" LED projection used for quick target acquisition. The Aimpoint Pro can be mounted on M1913 standard Picatinny rail.

The optic provides 4 NVD *(Night Vision) settings and 6 day time brightness settings.

The sight is housed in high strength aluminum that protects the optic against damage it may face Military/LE conditions.

This is more stress than any civilian weapon will never be put under. Simply put this Optic is extremely durable!

It is water resistant and is submersible to 150ft. 

The Optic has a continuous use (Always in the on position) of over 30,000 hours, or 3 years with one battery. One 3V Lithium battery, type 2L76 or DL1/3N is used to power this Optic. 

This optic was mounted on my Daniel Defense, (DDM4LE). After sighting in the optic and around 5,000 rounds put down range, it has kept its zero and never needed to be re-sighted. Even at 100 yards this sights is extremely accurate and makes an unexperienced shooter look like a pro. It is best suited for closer range an allows for quick target acquisition. 

I have experience with many optics and I will say it is an excellent sight for the price and I have zero complaints about how it has preformed. 

I have had it for less than one year, and it has approximately 20 hours of battery use. When not in use, the sight along with my weapon is stored in an air/dust/ moisture tight Pelican Case. It has never been dropped, has no damage and works perfectly. 

I am selling my Aimpoint Pro to fund another gun purchase. 

This sight sells new for around $415 without tax and shipping. For $300 this is a very good deal for someone looking for a very high quality optic.

I have the original factory manual and comes with the Aimpoint Pro mount and lens covers. 

I have posted a link to Aimpoint's website with more specific information. You can also look at reviews on youtube and online and you will find it has excellent reviews. 

I have also posted several pictures of mine mounted on my weapon and the sight by its self. 

Serious buyers only.

Excellent condition with no scratches or damage
LED red dot

3 years of continuous battery life

This is the earlier metal-folder version of the BC stock, not the later all-composite version. It locks in the folded and open positions very positively with no slop or play and includes a nice interchangeable 1" rubber buttpad that extends the length of pull over the factory stock a little over 1". It has a neat storage compartment built in to the pistol grip that has a removable sliding door to store batteries, cleaning accessories, etc.
